	L0V__3Erxv [label=<
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="#add8ff" WIDTH="150"><B>Analysis</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">In my opinion, the answer to plaintiff&#x27;s<BR ALIGN='left'/>contention that both voting and<BR ALIGN='left'/>nonvoting stock was issued to Maybar<BR ALIGN='left'/>stockholders, is, that under the<BR ALIGN='left'/>fundamental provisions of plaintiff&#x27;s<BR ALIGN='left'/>charter, both preferred and common were<BR ALIGN='left'/>voting stocks, and which happened to be<BR ALIGN='left'/>the voting stock at a particular time<BR ALIGN='left'/>was incidental. See Finding of Fact XII.<BR ALIGN='left'/>The requirement &quot;solely for all or a<BR ALIGN='left'/>part of its voting stock&quot; is intended to<BR ALIGN='left'/>rule out from the provisions of<BR ALIGN='left'/>subsection (g)(1)(B) transactions in<BR ALIGN='left'/>which there is an additional cash or<BR ALIGN='left'/>other valuable consideration and to<BR ALIGN='left'/>preserve the continuity of interest<BR ALIGN='left'/>requirement which is here represented by<BR ALIGN='left'/>two classes of stock, issued as a unit,<BR ALIGN='left'/>to be voted in the alternative.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
>]
